Same issue in the movie <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravity_(2013_film)" title="wikipedia.org">Gravity</a> [wikipedia.org].<br>
From <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2013/10/21/heres-what-gravity-gets-right-and-wrong-about-space/" title="washingtonpost.com">Here&rsquo;s what &lsquo;Gravity&rsquo; gets right and wrong about space</a> [washingtonpost.com]:</p><p><div class="quote"><p> <b>Q: 1. The Hubble Space Telescope, the International Space Station and China&rsquo;s Tiangong-1 are close enough to travel between them.<br>
A: False.</b> They&rsquo;re so far apart, in fact, that it&rsquo;s difficult to visualize. Not only are the three at different altitudes, but they&rsquo;re also on different orbits &mdash; making it very unusual for them to even get within a few hundred miles of each other.  In fact, when Cuaron asked Grazier about that particular issue, Grazier told him the closest the two would ever possibly get was &ldquo;the distance between here and Mexico.&rdquo; They were in Hollywood at the time.
</p><p>
<b>Q: 6. Space debris from a low-flying satellite could knock out communications satellites.<br>
A: False &mdash; mostly.</b> [see article for explanation]</p><p><div class="quote"></div></div></div>
