</li><li id="tree_64379272" class="comment oneline"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64379272" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64379272" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64379272" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64379272" name="comment_link_64379272" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23283730&amp;cid=64379272" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64379272)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64379272" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64379272); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Richard_at_work">Richard_at_work</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Richard_at_work">( 517087 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64379272"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64379272"><p>Orbital mechanics is a mind fuck all in its own.</p><p>Even if you are in an identical orbit to the ISS, and 500km behind it on the orbital path, how do you catch it up?</p><p>Well, you have to slow down.</p><p>By slowing down, you put yourself in a lower orbit, which actually is a shorter orbit, which means you orbit faster, which means you catch the ISS up.  You then speed back up to slow down to match the ISS orbit.</p><p>If you thrust yourself toward the ISS (ie by firing your rockets behind you), you slow down in relation to the<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64379272">

</div>
</div>

